''THUMP!THUMP!THUMP!'' You bolt straight up in your bed, startled by the sudden noise. It's late at night in your Shropshire farmhouse and you've gone to bed hours ago in preparation for an early rise. A yawn escapes you and you struggle to concentrate as the noise and low light tax your sluggish and still groggy senses, which are already not at thier peak. You blink several times before the pounding begins anew... ''THUMP!THUMP!THUMP!'' Dread begins to well up inside of you as you now recongize the familiar sound. Someone or some people are knocking on your door. But at this hour? Surely, nothing good could come of having company at this hour. You quickly spring from your bed and throw on an old shawl, draped over a lone chair. Your mind is racing to formulate a plan and recounting every person who might want something from you. You've paid your taxes and more, so that can't be it. Is it Marlow, the village drunkard? He's been chatting you up since before your husband was in the ground. Could it be your old pal Evelyn from up the road? She's always misplacing her needle here and thread there, and leaving her friends to foot the bill, plus she's up at all hours. Or maybe it's the young Edmund Tranter and his wife Molly. She's heavy with child and when you saw her on market day, you knew it couldn't be long. Jane, the local midwife is on the other side of your hill, but that hasn't stopped couples from paying you a visit by mistake before. And of course, Sheriff Dunn posted a reward for the apprehension of the local burglar not two weeks ago. "Please, for the love of Jesus, just let me inside..." You tense and hold your breath as this is a man's voice, though not Marlow's, Edmund's or Dunn's. Your needles may be safe, but are you? In the dim light, your eye catches the glint of your aging sickle, stashed in the corner. You've been meaning to hand it over to Walter, the blacksmith, along with a chicken in exchange for a new one, but you thank the Lord just this once for your sloth. You fetch it without hesitation. It might do you some good against an intrusion, and you doubt your abilites unarmed. But let's not get ahead of yourself, now. There could be a perfectly good explanation for this nocturnal disruption. You approach the door frame with your visitor still banging away and demanding to be let in. You would like very much to be back in the safety and warmth of your bed for a couple more hours, and maybe, if you ask nicely whoever's at the door will understand and go elsewhere. You could also find out who knocks, at risk to yourself, naturally. That's not very charitable; after all, the vicar says you won't know the hour when Jesus will come knocking. But if it's really Jesus, maybe he could wait until you washed up, and put on a fire. Finally, you could simply ignore the obviously desperate soul outside and hope for the best. ''THUMP!THUMP!THUMP!'' "Hello, Hello? Is anyone inside? Open up!" You stand with shaky hands and held breath, eyes fixated on the door, shuddering and jostling on its hinges. ''Do you...'' [[Swing the door open with the sickle raised high and poised to strike.]] [[Keep the door bolted but request the visitor identify themselves.]] [[Keep the door bolted and tell the visiot to scram.]] [[Hide in the corner and pretend that nobody is home]] Surprise is on your side, you reason. In one motion, you lift the wooden deadbolt and throw open the door, ready to cut the man down if he makes any move against you. This is when you get your first look at him. A gaunt man, close to your age, wearing a dishevled cloak. He carries no weapons that you can see, though not even a rucksack for that matter, which you find odd if he is travelling like he claims to be. Nevertheless its possible that some of what he tells you is true. Seeing you ready to attack, he falters bacward and raises his hands from under the dirty and ragged fabric. You quickly notice that he is clutching a large object, which he holds in front of himself like a shield. In the commotion, his hood falls back as his brooch unclasps, revealing his tonsure, an uncommon sight in 1540, at least in Merrie Olde England. He lets go of the bulky item for a moment as he grasps at the broach again, but not before the loose fabric gives one more secret and you catch a glimpse of your visitor's chasuble. "No! Please, no!" he shreiks, unprepared for your onslaught. You pulse is rocketing from the encounter, and slowly begins to wane as you lower your hand. As endorphins retreat, your analytical mind returns and you realize two important facts about tonight's company. 1) he is a man of the cloth, and 2) a Catholic one at that.You clear your throat in order to speak and manage a determined inquiry, "Who is it?"
